      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"adaptation_kind\":\"Restructure\",\"safety_tier\":\"Green\",\"nudge_patch\":null,\"restructure_plan\":{\"revised_weekly_targets\":[{\"week_number\":1,\"weekly_target_km\":32},{\"week_number\":2,\"weekly_target_km\":36},{\"week_number\":3,\"weekly_target_km\":40}],\"revised_current_week_workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":360,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start even easier than usual — this is a low-stress day.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":26,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":360,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Conversational pace throughout. If legs still feel heavy, ease off further.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk or very slow jog to close.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 min very easy walk/jog to get blood moving.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5 min easy walk. Finish with light leg shakeout.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Keep this genuinely easy — effort should feel almost too comfortable. The goal is just to move and restore, not to accumulate load.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run (Tempo Substitute)\",\"target_distance_km\":7,\"target_duration_minutes\":42,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":360,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease in gradually.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":32,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":360,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Fully aerobic, no tempo effort this week. Notice how the legs feel compared to Monday.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Gentle finish.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 min easy walk or light jog.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5 min easy walk with leg swings and calf stretches.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This replaces the tempo session for this week. Swapping intensity for aerobic volume lets your legs reset while keeping the training stimulus alive. You might find the legs start to come around mid-run.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Short Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":5,\"target_duration_minutes\":32,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":375,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":375,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":32,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":375,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Pure recovery pace — slower than easy. No watch-staring, just feel.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with a 3-minute walk.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3-minute walk and light stretch.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is a shorter, gentler Friday than originally planned. Think of it as active recovery — keeping the legs ticking over without adding stress.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Reduced Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":11,\"target_duration_minutes\":66,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":360,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":375,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Very easy first 8 minutes to assess how the legs feel.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":360,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady easy effort. If power returns, great — if not, it is fine to cut to 9 km again.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":375,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Wind down with a gentle jog-to-walk finish.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"8 min very easy to let the body settle in before committing to the run.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"8 min easy wind-down. Hydrate and refuel within 30 minutes.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Target 11 km rather than the full 14 km. Long runs build aerobic foundation, but only when the body is ready to absorb them. An 11 km run done well is worth more than a 14 km run done on empty legs.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}],\"forward_path\":\"Week 2 steps back up to 36 km — about a 12% bump from this week's revised 32 km — with the tempo session returning at your prescribed threshold pace. Week 3 brings you to 40 km, which is right where the original Week 1 target was, and from there the original progression resumes. In practice that means roughly a 4-week ramp rather than 3 weeks to reach 48 km, but the fitness you build on recovered legs will consolidate far more effectively than fitness forced through fatigue. The sub-1:45 goal remains very much on the table — this adjustment protects the 14 weeks of quality work ahead of you.\"},\"net_load_delta\":-8,\"rationale\":\"Cutting the long run short when your legs had nothing left was exactly the right call — pushing through that kind of muscular fatigue rarely ends well, and the fact that your breathing was fine tells us this was a local leg-load issue rather than a fitness gap. Looking across the last three sessions together, there's a consistent thread: the tempo run came in around 45 seconds per km slower than your prescribed threshold band, Friday's easy run took noticeably longer than planned, and Sunday's long run ended at 9 km instead of 14 km with heavy legs from the first step. That pattern suggests your legs have accumulated more fatigue than the plan anticipated at this stage — probably the body adjusting to a new training block. So here's what's changed for this week: the tempo session becomes an easy aerobic run (same kind of low-stress movement, without the threshold demand), the long run is trimmed to 11 km at a fully comfortable pace, and Friday is a short recovery run to keep things ticking without adding load. The weekly total comes down to around 32 km, which gives your legs room to actually absorb the work you've already done. Week 2 steps back up to 36 km with threshold work returning, and Week 3 brings you to 40 km — from there the original build resumes on a much more solid foundation. You might find the legs feel noticeably fresher by Wednesday, and the path to sub-1:45 is very much intact.\",\"referral_category\":null}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
